<p />
<table style="margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" class="draggable toggleable-table">
<thead>
<tr>
<th id="x" style="text-align: right;">Source (Hebrew)</th>
<th style="text-align: left;">Translation (English)</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="vertical-align:top;">
<div class="liturgy" lang="he" style="text-align: right;">
</div>
</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;">
<div class="english" lang="en" style="text-align: left;">
(Citron and willow branch and palm.<br />
And myrtle leaves for fragrant balm<br />
We wave and sway with praise and psalm.)
</div>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="vertical-align:top;">
<div class="liturgy" lang="he" style="text-align: right;">
בָּרוּךְ אַתָּה יְיָ אֱלֹהֵֽינוּ<br />
מֶֽלֶךְ הָעוֹלָם אֲשֶׁר קִדְּשָׁנוּ בְּמִצְוֺתָיו וְצִוָּֽנוּ<br />
עַל נְטִילַת לוּלָב׃
</div>
</td>
<td style="vertical-align:top;">
<div class="english" lang="en" style="text-align: left;">
Blessed art thou, O God, our King,<br />
Lord of the world, who bade us bring<br />
The lulab&#8217;s harvest offering.
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />
<p>This rhyming paraphrase of the blessing before waving the lulav on Sukkot was written by Jessie Ethel Sampter and published in her <em>Around the Year in Rhymes for the Jewish Child</em> (1920), p. 17.</p>
